vectorData.altText: That's right!  This is the tunica albuginea. It is a dense irregular connective tissue capsule that surrounds the ovary. Its high collagen content accounts for its eosinophilic appearance.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

This histological representation of the ovary has been zoomed in to illustrate the surface epithelium (E), tunica albuginea (TA) and cortex (C) (only part of which is shown). The surface epithelium is made up of simple cuboidal epithelium, which is continuous with the mesovarium (not shown). Beneath the surface epithelium lies a layer of dense irregular CT, the tunica albuginea, which supports the surface epithelium. Deep to the tunica albuginea lies the cortex. Within the cortex one can find the developing ovarian follicles. The medulla (M) is not shown in this image.
